<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=
=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspace:0pt;word-b=
reak:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td style=3D"padding-bottom:22px;"><div style=
=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;=
;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:150%;text-al=
ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;"><strong>What are some actual, realistic options for cutting spending?=
=C2=A0</strong></p>
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;mar=
gin-bottom:0px;">The continuing resolution is keeping the government afloat=
 right now, and it expires on March 14. Trump has every opportunity availab=
le to him to decide before that, with his Republican Senate and House, what=
 programs get funded and what programs don=E2=80=99t. He has a budget that =
he can put out the first week of February that can lay out very explicitly =
what gets funded. What he <em>cannot</em> do is backtrack and
erase what Congress=E2=80=99s authority is, which is to appropriate money.=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">The problem yesterday was these agencies can=E2=
=80=99t decide what they fund and what they don=E2=80=99t fund. They can=E2=
=80=99t say to the president, =E2=80=9COh, what you=E2=80=99re doing is ill=
egal. You can=E2=80=99t tell us we can=E2=80=99t spend this money.=E2=80=9D=
 And so they have to play along until they get told something else, either =
by Congress or by the courts. I don=E2=80=99t know what=E2=80=99s
going on over there. It=E2=80=99s clearly amateur hour. <strong>Elon Musk</=
strong> is trying to run the government like Tesla or X, and he needs a tut=
orial in Appropriations 101.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>What=E2=80=99s t=
he reputation of the DOGE guys on the Hill?=C2=A0</strong></p><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">We=E2=80=99re trying to figure out which Democrats are going to be a pa=
rt of
[the congressional DOGE Caucus] and see if it=E2=80=99s going to be biparti=
san. A lot of people are taking them seriously, because they have to, and t=
hey are trying to decide if they should meet with them, or give briefings, =
or who the point people are going to be. This was just a total misstep yest=
erday. But moving forward, there are a lot of members on both sides who rea=
lize that government spending cuts are going to take place. And so if they =
want to be a part of where those happen, they should come
to the table and make their case.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px=
;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>Elon=E2=80=99=
s </strong><strong><em>modus operandi</em></strong><strong> is to break thi=
ngs and then rebuild them in a way that can=E2=80=99t be broken. Can you do=
 that to the government?=C2=A0</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">You can=E2=80=99t create somethin=
g that=E2=80=99s never going to change, because there are elections, and di=
fferent people
are in charge. You can certainly make changes in the government. But you ca=
n=E2=80=99t come in in a week and shut the whole thing down and try to star=
t over from scratch.</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
